UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440768690031X
AB  - Our paper develops a model of allocative distortions with which we analyze departures of the U.S. airline industry from efficient resource allocation during the period 1970–1981. Airline technology is assumed to transform capital, labor, energy, and materials into passenger and cargo service whose characteristics are endogeneously determined. A generalized-Leontief system of distorted profit, output supply, input demand, and reduced form output characteristics expressions is estimated by FIML using a multivariate error components model with vector autoregressive disturbances. Our results tend to support the common perception that deregulation reduced both the total cost and relative level of allocative distortions.
