DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(86)90027-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407686900278
AB  - Typically measures of multi-factor productivity growth have been based on a non-parametric framework that assumes all inputs are instantaneously adjustable, thus ignoring the important impacts of short-run fixity of certain inputs. This paper focuses on the representation within a parametric production model of economic capacity utilization indexes and on the adjustment of observed productivity measures by these indexes for the effects of short-run fixity. A dynamic optimization model based on adjustment costs for quasi-fixed inputs is developed to calculate these capacity utilization adjustments. The resulting framework is then used to identify empirically the effects of capacity utilization, non-static expectation, non-constant returns to scale and adjustment costs for both capital and labor on productivity growth in the U.S. manufacturing sector, 1947–1979.
