EP  - 284
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/10/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(86)90036-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407686900369
AB  - Temporary equilibrium production models for a common-property renewable-resource sector are developed and used to measure the shadow value of the resource. The structure of these models incorporates the biological dynamics and the ownership rights. Under sole ownership, the firm chooses the utilization level of the resource stock, which in turn affects his investment policy in the resource. For an open-access fishery, the firm behaves as if the shadow value was zero. To measure the shadow values for an open-access fishery, a model of downstream market behavior is proposed. This model is implemented for the North Pacific halibut fishery.
ER  - 
